6. RESULTS
------------------------------------------------------------

6.1 Unweighted candidate-profile tests

Fitted exponents for the three baseline stiffness models:

    Model                               Median ν
    ------------------------------------------------
    power-law stiffness                  0.940
    density-coupled stiffness            0.947
    exponential-core stiffness           0.950

The power-law stiffness reproduces the observed exponent exactly,
while the other physically motivated profiles generate similar
effective exponents across the SPARC radial window.


6.2 Weighted cumulative SPARC result

The later weighted cumulative tests identify an empirically preferred
local loading law

    m(r) ∝ g_b(r)^γ

with

    γ ≈ 0.34

and a preferred radial accumulation measure

    dμ_r = r^κ dr

with

    κ ≈ −0.2.

The resulting cumulative equation is

    dS/dr = r^κ ( g_b(r) / g_* )^γ.

Across the SPARC working sample this weighted cumulative law produces
a pooled master-curve exponent close to the observed value,

    ν_pooled ≈ 0.95.

The preferred weighted operator therefore reproduces the observed
master-curve exponent to good accuracy.


6.3 Weighted horizon law

Using the same values

    γ ≈ 0.34,
    κ ≈ −0.2,

the weighted cumulative field yields the weighted horizon fraction

    f_k = S_k(R_s) / S_{k,tot}

with

    S_k(r) = ∫_0^r s^κ m(s) ds.

Defining

    τ = r_max / R_s

and the weighted local horizon diagnostic

    μ_k = R_s^(1+κ) m(R_s) / S_k(R_s),

the SPARC working sample satisfies the two-variable weighted horizon
law

    log f_k = A + b log τ + c ( μ_k − μ_0 )

with fitted coefficients

    A   ≈ −0.424
    b   ≈ −0.586
    c   ≈ −0.619
    μ_0 ≈ 1.148

and goodness of fit

    R^2 ≈ 0.941.

This is substantially stronger than the corresponding one-variable
projection law.


6.4 Global stiffness-threshold fit

A single global stiffness coupling constant

    A_stiff ≈ 0.0489

was fitted so that the weighted cumulative field satisfies

    S(R_s) ≈ S_c

across the SPARC sample.

With this single global normalization, the distribution of stiffness
at the observed turnover radius is

    median S(R_s) = 1.00
    25–75% range  ≈ 0.63 – 1.33.

This indicates that the turnover radius corresponds to a nearly
universal cumulative stiffness threshold.



------------------------------------------------------------
7. DISCUSSION
------------------------------------------------------------

7.1 Interpretation of the exponent

The observed master-curve exponent

    ν ≈ 0.94

implies in the simple unweighted case

    S(r) ∼ r^0.94

and therefore

    m(r) ∼ r^−0.06.

Thus the stiffness field is nearly constant with radius with a mild
outward decline.


7.2 Physical interpretation

This behaviour is consistent with

    • shallow background stiffness
    • finite inner stiffness excess
    • density-coupled curvature stiffness.

All three mechanisms produce cumulative stiffness growth that is
close to linear but slightly sublinear.


7.3 Connection to baryonic loading

The empirical local stiffness field recovered in the Colab tests is

    m(r) ∝ g_b(r)^γ

with

    γ ≈ 0.34.

If baryonic acceleration behaves approximately as

    g_b(r) ∝ r^−q

then

    m(r) ∝ r^(−γ q).

In the weighted model the cumulative budget becomes

    S(r) = ∫_0^r s^κ g_b(s)^γ ds.

Thus the master-curve exponent reflects both baryonic loading and the
effective radial accumulation measure.


7.4 Background response field interpretation

The empirical results do not require baryons to generate the full
gravitational response field from nothing. A more accurate
interpretation is that an ambient response or stiffness field already
exists in the galactic gravitational sector, and that baryonic
structure modulates how strongly this field is locally loaded and
cumulatively activated.

Accordingly, the local stiffness is written as

    m(r) = m_bg(r) + δm_b(r),

where

    m_bg(r)

is the background response field and

    δm_b(r)

is the baryonic modulation.

The simplest tested modulation law is

    m(r) = m_0 + B ( g_b(r) / g_* )^γ,

where

    m_0

is the background stiffness floor,

    B

is the baryonic coupling amplitude,

and

    γ ≈ 0.34

is the fitted baryonic response exponent.

In this form, baryons do not create the field itself; rather, they
increase the local stiffness above a background level.



