9. CONCLUSION
------------------------------------------------------------

A cumulative-stiffness description of gravity naturally generates the
empirical master curve of galactic rotation curves.

The chain

    m(r)
      ↓
    S(r) = ∫ cumulative stiffness budget
      ↓
    V(r)/V_inf

produces the observed stretched-exponential velocity profile when
cumulative stiffness behaves approximately as a power law across the
observed radial interval.

The original unweighted interpretation corresponds to a nearly
constant gravitational stiffness field with a mild outward decline.
The later weighted cumulative analysis shows that the SPARC data favour
a more specific operator-based description in which

    m(r) ∝ g_b(r)^0.34

and

    dS/dr = r^(−0.2) m(r).

This same weighted cumulative law reproduces the master-curve exponent
and yields a strong weighted two-variable horizon relation across the
SPARC working sample.

The preferred physical interpretation is not that baryons generate the
entire gravitational response field, but that they modulate an ambient
response field already present in the gravitational sector. The central
remaining first-principles problem is therefore the origin of the
effective radial accumulation measure

    dμ_r = r^(−0.2) dr

or equivalently the effective radial metric coefficient

    g_rr = r^(−0.4).



