2.X SELF-CONSISTENT METRIC CLOSURE
------------------------------------------------------------

The empirical weighted cumulative law can be embedded in a coupled
metric-stiffness system rather than imposed directly as a fitted
one-dimensional operator.

We write the effective radial metric in the form

    dℓ^2 = exp[2ψ(r)] dr^2 + r^2 dΩ^2,

so that the proper radial measure is

    du = exp[ψ(r)] dr.

The cumulative stiffness field then obeys

    dS/dr = exp[ψ(r)] m(r).

For the baryonic loading law identified from the SPARC tests we take

    m(r) = B ( g_b(r) / g_* )^γ,

with

    γ ≈ 0.34.

The cumulative field equation is therefore

    dS/dr = exp[ψ(r)] B ( g_b(r) / g_* )^0.34.


2.X.1 Saturated metric response

The simplest successful nontrivial metric closure found in the Colab
tests was a normalized saturated response of the radial metric to the
cumulative stiffness field. Defining

    q(r) = r ψ'(r),

the metric sector is taken to satisfy

    d/dr [ r ψ'(r) ]
      = η [ 1 - exp(−S(r)/S_c) ] / S(R_s),

where S(R_s) is the self-consistently determined cumulative stiffness
at the fitted turnover radius.

This gives the coupled system

    dS/dr = exp[ψ(r)] B ( g_b(r) / g_* )^0.34

    d/dr [ r ψ'(r) ] = η [ 1 - exp(−S/S_c) ] / S(R_s).

The effective weighted exponent is then not inserted by hand, but is
generated dynamically as

    κ_eff(r) = r ψ'(r).


2.X.2 Local horizon-state stabilization

Direct tests of the saturated metric response reproduce the observed
weighted exponent in the sample median, but leave substantial
galaxy-to-galaxy scatter. Scatter diagnostics show that the remaining
dispersion correlates with the local horizon-state variable

    μ_k(r) = r m(r) / S(r),

where

    m(r) = exp[−ψ(r)] dS/dr.

The most successful refined closure therefore introduces a local
stabilizer centered on the sample horizon state μ_0:

    d/dr [ r ψ'(r) ]
      = η [ 1 - exp(−S/S_c) ] / S(R_s)
        × 1 / [ 1 + λ ( μ_k(r) - μ_0 )^2 ].

The full best-tested system is thus

    dS/dr = exp[ψ(r)] B ( g_b(r) / g_* )^0.34

    d/dr [ r ψ'(r) ]
      = η [ 1 - exp(−S/S_c) ] / S(R_s)
        × 1 / [ 1 + λ ( μ_k(r) - μ_0 )^2 ]

    V(r)/V_inf = 1 - exp[−S(r)/S_c].

The best-performing parameter values found in the working sample are

    B     ≈ 0.048905
    γ     ≈ 0.34
    η     ≈ −0.05
    λ     ≈ 0.5
    μ_0   ≈ 1.2995
    S_c   = 1
    m_0   = 0.


2.X.3 Interpretation

This closure has three important features.

First, the observed weighted radial exponent is no longer imposed as an
external fit. Instead it is generated dynamically through the metric
field variable

    κ_eff(r) = r ψ'(r).

Second, the geometry responds not to raw cumulative stiffness alone but
to a saturated stiffness activation,

    1 - exp(−S/S_c),

which prevents the strongest runaway behaviour found in unsaturated
closures.

Third, the local horizon-state stabilizer suppresses excessive radial
compression in galaxies whose local stiffness ratio deviates strongly
from the sample horizon state μ_0.

In this formulation the weighted operator

    dS/dr = r^κ m(r)

is replaced by a dynamically generated effective measure

    dS/dr = exp[ψ(r)] m(r),

with

    exp[ψ(r)] ≈ r^κ_eff(r)

over the observed galaxy window.



