6.X.1 Interpretation of the closure test

These results show that the empirically preferred weighted exponent is
not merely a static fitting artifact. A coupled metric-stiffness system
with a saturated metric response can generate

    κ_eff ≈ −0.2

self-consistently in the sample median, and the addition of a mild
local horizon-state stabilizer improves the internal consistency of the
closure.

The data therefore support the following hierarchy of descriptions:

1. the original weighted operator
       dS/dr = r^(−0.2) m(r)
   is an excellent effective summary of the galaxy-scale behaviour;

2. this operator can be generated approximately by a coupled metric
   field through
       exp[ψ(r)] ≈ r^κ_eff(r);

3. the most successful current first-principles candidate is the
   self-consistent μ_k-stabilized saturated metric closure written
   above.


6.X.2 Remaining limitation

The closure is not yet a final universal derivation. Although the
median effective exponent is reproduced accurately and the scatter is
reduced, substantial galaxy-to-galaxy variation remains in κ_eff(r).

Accordingly, the current status of the theory is:

    the weighted operator has been elevated from a fitted one-dimensional
    law to a dynamically generated effective metric response, but the
    local stabilization of κ_eff remains incomplete.

This is the remaining gap between the present effective-geometric
description and a fully derived first-principles galaxy-scale theory.



